vitamin D levels and low calcium levels","High calcium levels and low phosphate levels","Low parathyroid hormone levels and high calcium levels","High vitamin D levels and high calcium levels","Normal calcium levels and low parathyroid hormone levels"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn secondary hyperparathyroidism, the parathyroid glands produce excess parathyroid hormone. This condition is associated with chronic kidney disease, where impaired renal function leads to phosphate retention and reduced activation of vitamin D. Low vitamin D levels reduce calcium absorption in the small intestine. The \u003Cstrong\u003Elow vitamin D levels and low calcium levels\u003C/strong\u003E stimulate the parathyroid glands to secrete more parathyroid hormone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh calcium levels and low phosphate levels\u003C/strong\u003E are not the derangements expected in secondary hyperparathyroidism. High calcium levels would suppress parathyroid hormone secretion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow parathyroid hormone levels and high calcium levels\u003C/strong\u003E suggest malignancy-related hypercalcaemia, not secondary hyperparathyroidism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh vitamin D levels and high calcium levels\u003C/strong\u003E would suppress parathyroid hormone secretion, which is not consistent with secondary hyperparathyroidism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal calcium levels and low parathyroid hormone levels\u003C/strong\u003E are not characteristic of secondary hyperparathyroidism, where elevated parathyroid hormone levels are expected due to low calcium levels.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Secondary hyperparathyroidism is caused by chronic kidney disease, leading to low calcium and high phosphate levels.","In secondary hyperparathyroidism, parathyroid hormone levels are elevated in response to low calcium levels.","Vitamin D deficiency contributes to secondary hyperparathyroidism by reducing calcium absorption."],"references":["Rodr\u00edguez-Ortiz ME, Rodr\u00edguez M. Recent advances in understanding and managing secondary hyperparathyroidism in chronic kidney disease. F1000Res. 2020 Sep 1;9:F1000 Faculty Rev-1077. doi: 10.12688/f1000research.22636.1. PMID: 32913635; PMCID: PMC7463297.","Muppidi V, Meegada SR, Rehman A. Secondary Hyperparathyroidism. [Updated 2023 Aug 28]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557822/","Habas E Sr, Eledrisi M, Khan F, Elzouki AY. Secondary Hyperparathyroidism in Chronic Kidney Disease: Pathophysiology and Management. Cureus. 2021 Jul 14;13(7):e16388. doi: 10.7759/cureus.16388. PMID: 34408941; PMCID: PMC8362860."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61387"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17741"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61387"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T07:18:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T07:19:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10455"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75874"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{